Doc,<br><br>
Once again you use the expression &quot;in vain&quot;.  The use of this expression in any context is offensive to those who have given their best.  We teach our sports heroes that the game is the most important aspect.  Their are always winners and losers.  A shame.  I am sure as a shrink you convince your patients that the world is predominantly losers.  Makes them feel better.  Must all losers feel they have spent their life in vain.  Did you graduate at the top of your class or achieve exactly what you sought. In vain?   Searching for some greater truth.  In vain?  Nasty thought isn't it.<br><br>
Doc, your quote about my description of a warrior is correct as far as it goes.<br><br>
&quot;Silent Warrior knows what I am talking about,warriors come in all colors and sizes, schools and traditions, levels and deeds. It is the intention that defines the act, not the act that defines the intention.&quot;  CORRECT<br><br>
What is missed is warriors are not always on the same side or do they strive for the same purpose.  This the reason warriors will struggle.  To ask them to change is take away that special quality that makes them a warrior.  All superior warriors look to a Chief for quidance.  Who was yours.  You know who ours was.  It could not possibly have been the same as the US soldier's Commander and Chief.  Sorry logic is brutal.<br><br>
I do disagree with your contention that the 58,000 were from the wrong side of the tracks.  They were from all walks of life and educational backgrounds.  I for one have a real friend who was a congressmans son and served three + tours.  Personal thing you know.<br><br>
With your definition we are to assume after thorough evaluation that all wars were in vain.  The Germans and Japanese are still kicking our ass.  Just chose a different battlefield. (Ever hear of Gaming Theory?)<br><br>
I do not walk the common path and I will never be alone.  Those that walk with me I can trust.  I work with Navy, Marines, Air Force, and Army soldiers and vets daily.  One thing you must remember, a Marine places the same dedication to his job as he does his wars.  I see the same from all warriors.  A matter of character I am sure.<br><br>
Certain bridges are never built because no ones wants to go to the other side.<br>

